  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most vendors have a general sense that their agent is managing the sale, but the specifics of what that actually involves can be surprisingly unclear. When you sign a Form 6 authority, you are engaging someone to represent your interests through a process that typically spans four to six weeks and involves significant legal and financial obligations. Knowing what your agent should be doing at each stage makes it easier to hold them accountable and to recognise when you are getting real value versus warm reassurance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Before the property goes to market</h2>
      <p>The pre-listing phase is where a lot of the outcome is determined. A good agent will spend time with you walking through the property to identify presentation issues that are worth addressing before photography. This is not about undertaking a full renovation. It is about clearing clutter, fixing visible maintenance items, and deciding whether professional styling is likely to produce a measurable return in your price bracket and suburb.</p>

      <p>Your agent should also brief you on comparable sales in detail. Not just a printed report of recent transactions, but a genuine conversation about what those sales tell you about buyer expectations, likely price range, and how your property compares. This is the basis on which your pricing strategy and campaign method should be decided, so you need to understand their reasoning, not just their conclusion.</p>

      <p>The marketing plan should be confirmed before you sign anything. This includes where the property will be advertised, what photography and video is included, whether floor plans are being prepared, and the total marketing budget. In Brisbane's inner east, professional photography is non-negotiable. Drone footage and video walkthroughs are standard for family homes in the $1 million-plus range. Anything less suggests your agent is managing their cost of acquisition, not maximising your result.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">During the campaign</h2>
      <p>Once the property is live, your agent has several active responsibilities running in parallel. The most visible is managing open homes. This means being present, engaging meaningfully with buyers, tracking attendance numbers and buyer quality, and following up with every attendee within 24 hours. Passive open homes where the agent stands by the door and hands out brochures are not generating the feedback or the buyer relationships that lead to competitive offers.</p>

      <p>Your agent should also be working their database proactively. Buyers who have been searching in your suburb and price range for several months are often the most motivated. A well-run buyer database means your property may have been pitched to qualified buyers before it even went live online. If your agent cannot tell you how many buyers from their database they contacted directly in the first week of your campaign, that is a gap worth raising.</p>

      <p>Regular vendor updates are part of your agent's obligation, not a courtesy. You should be receiving structured feedback after every open home: how many groups attended, what buyers said, what price feedback was recorded, and whether there are any parties requesting private inspections. If you are receiving generic "the market is interested" updates rather than specific data, ask for the detail. The quality of feedback you receive directly affects the decisions you make about pricing and timing.</p>

      <p>Negotiating offers is where the agent's skill has the most direct impact on your financial outcome. When offers come in, your agent should be managing the process actively, not just passing written numbers between you and buyers. A good negotiator understands buyer motivation and financing, knows when to hold firm and when to engage, and can move multiple parties toward competition. If you have only one buyer and your agent accepts the first number without attempting to establish competition or improve terms, you may have left money on the table.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After the contract is signed</h2>
      <p>Many vendors assume the agent's work is done once the contract is executed. In practice, the period between contract signing and settlement carries real risk, and your agent should be active throughout it. In Queensland, buyers have a cooling-off period of five business days from contract signing. Your agent should monitor this period and maintain contact with the buyer to ensure any questions are addressed promptly.</p>

      <p>If the contract includes a finance condition, your agent should be tracking the finance date and maintaining regular contact with the buyer's broker or bank. Delays in finance approval are one of the most common causes of settlement complications. An agent who monitors this proactively can often pre-empt problems before they become a formal dispute.</p>

      <p>The pre-settlement inspection, typically scheduled two to three days before settlement, gives the buyer the right to inspect the property to confirm it is in the same condition as when contracts were exchanged. Your agent should brief you on what to expect and help manage any issues that arise, rather than leaving you to handle a last-minute dispute with the buyer directly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What good communication looks like</h2>
      <p>Throughout the campaign, the quality of your agent's communication is a reliable proxy for the quality of their work overall. Agents who are genuinely managing your campaign proactively have specific information to report. They know which buyers attended each open home, what price feedback those buyers gave, which parties have requested contracts, and what the realistic path to an offer looks like. Vague updates are usually a sign that the behind-the-scenes work is not happening.</p>

      <p>You should also feel comfortable raising concerns or asking direct questions without your agent becoming defensive. The relationship is a professional one in which you are the client. If your agent cannot clearly explain why they are recommending a particular strategy, or if they discourage you from understanding the detail of what is happening, that is a problem worth addressing early rather than after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions worth asking before you list</h2>
      <p>Before signing with any agent, ask them specifically: how many buyers in your database are currently active at my price point and in this suburb? How often will you update me, and in what format? Who else from your team will be involved in managing open homes or buyer follow-up? What happens if we receive no offers after three weeks, and what is your recommendation at that point?</p>

      <p>An agent who can answer these questions clearly and specifically is prepared to run your campaign professionally. An agent who gives you generic answers about market conditions and their track record without addressing the specifics is telling you more than they realise about how they will manage your sale.</p>

